<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic Offers To Withdraw `Elements' of Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1202211494 Paris AFP in English 2054 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1202211494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Feb 12 (AFP) -- Croatia is prepared to 
withdraw "elements" of its army currently fighting in Bosnia if 
the UN pledges to guarantee the security of Croat enclaves in 
central Bosnia, Foreign Minister Mate Granic said Saturday [12 
February]. 
  Granic told journalists he made the proposal in a letter 
Friday to United Nations Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali. 
  As well as proposing the withdrawal of "elements" of its 
army 
deployed south of the southern Bosnia-Herzegovina city of 
Mostar, Zagreb also called on the UN to set up frontier controls 
on the border between Bosnia and Croatia. 
  "At the same time, Croatia is asking for guarantees from the 
UN concerning the security of the Croat enclaves in central 
Bosnia," Granic added. 
  The troops in question were deployed on both sides of the 
Neretva River along a 27-kilometre (16-mile) corridor between 
the border and the town of Buna, south of Mostar, Granic added. 
  Granic said the troops stationed east of the river were 
Croatian Army regulars, and those on the western bank were 
"former members of the Croatian Army" fighting as "volunteers" 
alongside Bosnian Croat forces. 
  On February 3, the UN Security Council called on Croatia to 
immediately withdraw all its regular forces from Bosnia or face 
international sanctions. 
  The UN has estimated between 3,000 and 5,000 Croatian 
regulars are fighting in Bosnia. 
  Zagreb has denied the allegation, but admitted it has 
deployed troops south of Mostar and in the hinterland of the 
Croatian Adriatic port of Dubrovnik, and that around 2,000 
Croatian military "volunteers" are active inside Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

