<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Determined Not To Resign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1202184394 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1700 
GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1202184394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] An extraordinary meeting of the HZDS [Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia] leadership is being held in Modra near 
Bratislava today. The meeting is to discuss differences of 
views that have clearly taken shape within the past few days. 
Our colleague Renata Havranova, editor of the PRACE daily, 
reports: 
  [Havranova] The extraordinary session of the HZDS national 
leadership is to decide today about the stance to be taken by 
the ruling movement on solving a serious political crisis in 
Slovakia--the crisis that was brought about by the HZDS itself, 
with some SNS [Slovak National Party] deputies, by obstructions 
in the [Slovak] parliament. Since early this morning, the Modra 
hotel has been totally closed to journalists. 
  [HZDS] press spokeswoman Ivana Salczerova confirmed that 
Prime Minister [Vladimir] Meciar had taken the floor, as he had 
promised, to give his view on the Alternative of Political 
Realism formed in Papiernicka, which is being supported by nine 
deputies--one of the original 10 signatories has withdrawn its 
signature--and two government members, [Deputy Prime Minister] 
Roman Kovac and [Foreign Minister] Jozef Moravcik. Meciar is 
said to have described once again their appeal to immediately 
form a government of broad coalition without political heads as 
an immoral, undemocratic appeal contradicting the movement's 
principles. According to Meciar, the action taken by Moravcik 
and Kovac is a dirty trick, not only on him personally but also 
on the entire government and all of its members. 
  This afternoon, journalists came across Jozef Moravcik 
walking in the streets of this little town. He confirmed to 
them that the discussion was very sharp and that all those who 
had joined the Alternative were probably going to be pacified by 
the [HZDS] leadership. He also said that a proposal was voiced 
asking him and Roman Kovac to resign. He is determined not to 
resign. According to Minister Moravcik, whatever decision is 
made at today's session of the leadership, there is no doubt 
that the shaping of views has already begun, and it is no longer 
possible to halt it. 

</TEXT>

