<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TANJUG: Akashi Halts Artillery Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1302195294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1936 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1302195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, February 13 (TANJUG) -- Special United 
Nations envoy for former Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi has stopped 
the artillery withdrawal around Sarajevo assessing that the 
Bosnian Serbs' heavy weapons could be efficiently controlled 
where they are at present, Chief of the General Staff of the 
Serbian Army General Manojlo Milovanovic said on Sunday. 
  "The reason for stopping the withdrawal of artillery pieces 
is that the U.N. peacekeepers (UNPROFOR) are unable to secure 
efficient control of the Moslem infantry, which is envisaged by 
an agreement reached by the Moslem and Serb sides and UNPROFOR," 
General Milovanovic told a press conference after meeting with 
Chief of the UNPROFOR Command for Bosnia Angus Ramsey. 
  General Milovanovic and Ramsey met at Pale, the political 
centre of the Bosnian Serb Republic, to discuss Sarajevo's 
demilitarization and control of the agreed ceasefire which took 
effect at noon on Thursday. 
  The Bosnian Serb army has proposed that its artillery be 
controlled on its present positions with simultaneous control of 
the Moslem infantry because the Serb heavy weapons are a balance 
to the more numerous Moslem infantry, General Milovanovic said. 
  As UNPROFOR has failed to secure the control of the Moslem 
infantry Milovanovic said he did not allow the Serb artillery to 
be withdrawn. 
  The relevant documents, including NATO's ultimatum, do not 
insist categorically on a withdrawal of the artillery because 
they use the terms "withdrawal" and "placing under UNPROFOR 
control," he said. 
  "We have fulfilled our obligation by accepting to put our 
artillery under control on condition that the same is done with 
the Moslem infantry," General Milovanovic said. 
  Asked whether he took NATO threats seriously, he replied 
that, as a soldier, he did. 
  "I don't know what NATO will do but I know what we'll do - 
we'll defend ourselves," he said. 
  The North Atlantic Council on Wednesday gave ten days to the 
Bosnian Serbs to withdraw their heavy weapons 20 kilometres from 
the centre of Sarajevo or to place them under UNPROFOR control, 
or their positions would be bombed. 
  NATO also demanded from the Moslem side to place its heavy 
arms under UNPROFOR control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

