<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK Government on `Unprovoked Ultimatum' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1402224994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2223 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1402224994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, February 14 (TANJUG) -- The Foreign 
Ministry of the Republic of Serb Krajina (RSK) on Monday sent to 
all diplomatic and consular missions in Belgrade a note warning 
that the NATO ultimatum to the Bosnian Serbs was based on false 
premises. 
  On February 9, the NATO council threatened to launch air 
strikes against the Bosnian Serbs unless they withdrew their 
heavy artillery 20 kilometres from the centre of Sarajevo within 
ten days. 
  The unprovoked ultimatum is based on two false premises, the 
first being that the Bosnian Serbs are responsible for the 
massacre in Sarajevo on February 5 and the second that the 
Bosnian Serb Army is keeping Sarajevo under siege, the RSK 
ministry said in the note, which also includes a declaration of 
the RSK Parliament on solidarity with the Serbs in the former 
Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina adopted on Saturday. 
  All well-meaning people have realised that only the Moslem 
authorities in that part of the city could have caused the 
explosion, the note says. 
  "The untruth that Sarajevo is under a Serb seige has been 
fostered over the past two years by the Western media and it now 
seems beyond question. The truth, however, is different because 
the city is actually divided on Serb and Moslem parts which are 
both contiguous to their respective states," the RSK Foreign 
Ministry said in the note. 
  The RSK authorities and Army see NATO's ultimatum as a 
hostile act also against the RSK, which is ready to help the 
Bosnian Serb Republic in its defence from a possible aggression, 
it said. 
  The RSK was proclaimed in 1991 in the Serb-populated areas 
within the administrative borders of the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Croatia in response to Croatia's secession from the 
former Yugoslav Federation and the attempt to downgrade the 
status of the Serbs from that of the constituent people to that 
of an ethnic minority. 
  In March 1992, the RSK territory was proclaimed a United 
Nations Protected Area (UNPA). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

