<H3> <TI>   Sanctions To Be Discussed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1402092494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 0824 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1402092494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Belgrade, 14 Feb (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Prime 
Minister Radoje Kontic left for New York early today at the 
invitation of the New York-based Council for International 
Relations, the most influential institution of its kind in the 
United States. 
  Just before his departure Kontic said that there are a 
number 
of reasons for his visit to New York. [passage omitted] 
  "We will use our stay in New York to contact top UN 
officials, particularly UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali and 
his aides, as well as officials of various UN agencies." 
  According to Kontic the main topic of the talks will be the 
NATO ultimatum and the threat to bomb the Bosnian Serbs. "We 
will discuss this issue from two aspects. One of them is the 
position and the role of the United Nations in adopting concrete 
decisions on air strikes, and the other aspect is the 
consequences and dangers for the peace process and a possible 
escalation of the war if NATO threats are realized." 
  "Of course, an unavoidable topic in the United Nations will 
be the sanctions against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, the 
humanitarian aid, and the reintegration of our state in the 
system of the United Nations and the international community." 
[passage omitted] 
  Recalling the NATO ultimatum, Kontic concluded: "I do not 
believe that there is one serious reason at this moment for NATO 
to realize its threats and bomb the Bosnian Serbs. I believe 
that the purpose of this visit to New York is to help ease the 
tension." 

</TEXT>

