<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin, Milosevic Criticize NATO Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1302104494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 0959 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1302104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 13 Feb (TANJUG) -- Serbian President 
Slobodan Milosevic last night received Vitaliy Churkin, Russian 
deputy minister for foreign affairs and President Yeltsin's 
special envoy. 
  In the course of extensive and open talks, the Serbian 
president's office reports, views were exchanged regarding the 
efforts to put an end to the civil war in the area of 
ex-Bosnia-Herzegovina and find a political solution to the 
crisis. They stressed that NATO's decision has undoubtedly 
inflicted political damage on the negotiating process for 
ex-Bosnia-Herzegovina. Agreement was expressed to the effect 
that there is no alternative to political negotiations as the 
only sensible path that can lead to a stable peace in this area. 
  In this context it was pointed out that reduced tensions in 
the Sarajevo area would represent a significant step toward 
securing a political solution, as this would avert the risk of 
foreign military intervention and an escalation of warfare with 
far-reaching consequences for peace and stability in this part 
of Europe. 

</TEXT>

