<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bukoshi Views NATO Ultimatum as `Brave' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1202204494 Tirana TVSH Television Network in Albanian 1900 
GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1202204494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana TVSH Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Albanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dr. Bujar Bukoshi, prime minister of the republic 
of Kosova, sent a letter to the governments of NATO member 
countries, in which he supports the ultimatum of this alliance 
on withdrawal of artillery from Sarajevo. This ultimatum is a 
brave step, Dr. Bukoshi states, to be distinguished from the 
previous threats of the West, which were not realized. Those 
threats only made the aggressor brave and diminished the 
credibility of international powers. 
  Peace in the Balkans is not possible without resolving the 
Kosova crisis, Prime Minister Bukoshi stresses further on in the 
letter. Kosova once again asks the United States to intensify 
pressures against the Belgrade regime so as to interrupt the 
systematic oppression against the Albanian people in Kosova, 
Bukoshi underlines. 
  In this letter, Prime Minister Bukoshi asks the West to 
influence the return democratic institutions and international 
observers to Kosova, as well as to respect the elementary rights 
of 2 million Albanians in Kosova. If an immediate preventive 
action is taken, there is still time for the international 
community to enable a peaceful solution to the question of 
Kosova before its citizens face the tragedy and horror that can 
be of greater proportions than what is happening in Bosnia, 
prime minister of the republic of Kosova writes among other 
things in his letter addressed to the governments of NATO member 
countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

