<F P=100> MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With Gligorov on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1402191094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1809 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1402191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Skopje, 14 Feb (TANJUG) -- Kiro Gligorov, 
president of the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, and 
Vitaliy Churkin, special envoy of the Russian president, said in 
Skopje today that the conflicts in Bosnia-Herzegovina and the 
former Yugoslavia should be resolved by political means. 
  This is what Churkin told reporters after his talks with 
Gligorov. Churkin cautioned that any kind of escalation of war 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina would have consequences for the entire 
Yugoslav area and that the conflict might even spread beyond the 
borders of the former Yugoslavia. 
  The special envoy of the Russian president, who is on a 
one-day visit to Skopje, said that Russia was the first to 
demand an end to the siege of Sarajevo but that Moscow continues 
to maintain that action ought to be confined to the legal 
framework of the UN Security Council, where clear and precise 
stands could be adopted and then implemented by the parties to 
the conflict. The means envisaged by UN documents should be 
used in order to secure the implementation of the UN Security 
Council's decisions, Churkin said. 
  The situation in Sarajevo is such that the demilitarization 
of the city is needed as well as the lifting of the siege. If 
the demilitarization and the lifting of the blockade are not 
implemented, air strikes will follow, but that will also mean an 
escalation of conflicts with unforeseeable consequences, the 
special envoy pointed out. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

