<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rose `Determined'; Arms Handover Halted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402204794 Paris AFP in English 2031 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Feb 14 (AFP) -- UN General Michael Rose on 
Monday [14 February] said he was determined to enforce a "total 
exclusion zone" of heavy weapons around the Bosnian capital 
Sarajevo, as an agreed arms handover ground to a halt. 
  Rose, commander of the UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) in 
Bosnia, said all heavy weapons within 20 kilometres (12 miles) 
of Sarajevo "will either come under UNPROFOR control or will be 
subject to air attack." 
  The decision applied "to all weapons, it doesn't matter 
which 
army is in possession," he added, dispelling doubts about 
differences on the issue between the UN and the North Atlantic 
Treaty Organisation. 
  Last Wednesday NATO said both sides faced airstrikes if they 
did not withdraw heavy weapons from positions around Sarajevo or 
place them under UN supervision. Since then, some observers 
have questioned whether UNPROFOR was too lenient in allowing 
Serb forces to put heavy guns under "observation" rather than 
handing them over to full UN control. 
  Since Friday the Moslem-led Bosnian army has put 10 mortar 
guns under full UN control. The Serbs have put 33 of their guns 
under UN observation, but at Serb barracks. 
  No arms handover from either side took place on Monday, but 
negotiations to unblock the process were continuing, UNPROFOR 
spokesman Richard Pernod said at a press conference. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31107 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu031_i_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-031 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Satisfied Cease-Fire Respected </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402152394 Paris AFP in English 1517 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402152394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Brussels, Feb 14 (AFP) -- The North Atlantic 
Treaty Organisation is largely satisfied with a four-day-old 
ceasefire around the Bosnia-Herzegovina capital of Sarajevo, a 
senior NATO official said here Monday [14 February]. 
  NATO deputy secretary-general Sergio Silvio Balanzino told 
journalists: "For the time being we notice with satisfaction 
that the truce, the ceasefire, is being by and large respected." 
  The ceasefire began on Thursday one day after NATO warned 
that it would launch air strikes against Bosnian Serb artillery 
encircling Sarajevo unless it was withdrawn or placed under 
United Nations control by midnight next Sunday. 
  But Balanzino brushed aside a question about demands from 
the 
Bosnian Serbs that they should be allowed to retain the 
artillery in their own quarters, subject to UN surveillance, 
instead of physically handing the weapons over. 
  "The goal is to have the guns and heavy weapons put under 
control. Now there could be a variety of controls. As to 
techniques, these are steps to be worked out," Balanzino said, 
refusing to elaborate any further. [passage omitted] 
  A senior UN officer warned in Sarajevo that air strikes were 
inevitable if no substantial withdrawal of the Serb guns had 
taken place by Friday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31108 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu031_i_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-031 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Violate Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502093594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0900 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1502093594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] This morning is marked by persistent Chetnik 
provocations along some defense lines of Sarajevo -- 
particularly the area of Sokolje, which early this morning was 
exposed to fire from a death sower [M-84 machine gun] from the 
direction of Rajlovac. The same area was shelled by 60-mm 
mortars and later came under antiaircraft-gun fire. 
  Meanwhile, the Chetniks from (Lemizovo Brdo) were hurling 
grenades at the area of Izvor. 
  Chetnik snipers have also been used this morning; the one on 
Spicasta Stijena has been particularly active. Citizens are 
warned to be cautious if they must move around the city. 
  The Chetniks have not only violated the cease-fire this 
morning but have also been seen openly reinforcing their 
positions on several locations from where they can attack the 
city. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

