<H3> <TI>   UNPROFOR Broadly Interprets `Control' of Guns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402215194 Paris AFP in English 2103 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402215194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, Feb 14 (AFP) -- UN General Michael 
Rose on Monday [14 February] said he was determined to enforce a 
"total exclusion zone" of heavy weapons around the Bosnian 
capital Sarajevo, as an agreed arms handover ground to a halt. 
[passage omitted] 
  The UNPROFOR spokesman in Sarajevo, Lieutenant-Colonel Bill 
Aikman, said they were interpreting the term "control" in a 
broad sense. 
  "Troops do not have to stand beside each gun. But certainly 
we have a clear indication of where they are (...) whether 
they've been used (and) moved. Those are the sorts of ways of 
controlling them," he told journalists on Monday. [passage 
omitted] 
  An important meeting of Serb and Bosnian army chiefs, called 
by UNPROFOR, was expected to take place at Sarajevo airport on 
Tuesday morning. 

</TEXT>

