<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik: Control in Serbs' Interest </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1502005694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2356 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1502005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, February 14 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serbs want 
peace in Sarajevo, President of the Parliament of the Bosnian 
Serb republic Momcilo Krajisnik said on Monday and added that 
control of heavy artillery was in their interest. 
  "It is precisely because of the lack of such control that we 
have been unfoundedly accused so far," he said [word indistinct] 
a meeting with Andrea Colombo, head of the International 
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) European Office, in the 
Bosnian Serb political centre of Pale. 
  The two sides discussed humanitarian and political issues. 
  Krajisnik said he had conveyed to the ICRC official the 
stand 
of the Bosnian Serb leadership that the latest threat with NATO 
air strikes was "not an ultimatum to the Serb side because such 
a category in relations with the Serbian people is out of the 
question." 
  "We believe that this is pressure aimed at restoring peace 
in 
Sarajevo and controlling heavy weapons so that it could be 
established who initiates conflicts in this area," he said. 
  Krajisnik added that Colombo had informed him about visits 
of 
ICRC teams to prisons under Moslem control and promised to do 
everything in his power to ensure the earliest possible exchange 
of prisoners. 
  "Mr Colombo assured me that not a single member of the ICRC 
missions working in this area would leave our territory after 
NATO's ultimatum," he said. 
  Colombo said his visit was aimed at intensifying 
humanitarian 
operations in the entire area of the former Yugoslav republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, which entailed cooperation of all sides. 
  "I must point out the cooperativeness of the Serb side, 
which 
today again agreed to participate in the realisation of our 
programme," said Colombo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

