<H3> <TI>   UN To Send 11 Tanks to Tuzla Battalion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402210294 Paris AFP in English 2041 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402210294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Feb 14 (AFP) -- Eleven battle tanks will 
make a new effort to reach United Nations troops in the enclave 
of Tuzla, northeast Bosnia, Tuesday [15 February], after being 
held up for nearly five months, the UN command said here. 
  One hundred Danish troops will accompany the German-designed 
Leopards, the first heavy tanks to be used by the UN Protection 
Force (UNPROFOR) in Bosnia-Herzegovina, from Split in southern 
Croatia, the UN force said Monday. 
  The tanks were moved to Split to try to reach Tuzla from the 
south three weeks ago, after being prevented for four months by 
the Serbian authorities from leaving Pancevo, near Belgrade, on 
the grounds that they were offensive weapons. 
  Tuzla, held by the mainly-Moslem Bosnian armed forces, is 
being besieged by Bosnian Serb forces, who are resisting 
international pressure to reopen the airport there to 
humanitarian flights. 
  The Leopards will first head for Tomislavgrad in southwest 
Bosnia, which is under the control of Bosnian Croat militia, 
pending further orders from UNPROFOR. 
  They are destined for the 1,000-strong Nordic battalion of 
UNPROFOR in Tuzla. 

</TEXT>

