<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim-Croat Fighting Halts Humanitarian Convoys </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1502143594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1358 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1502143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Feb 15 (TANJUG) -- Fierce Muslim-Croat 
fighting on Tuesday prevented humanitarian convoys of the U.N. 
High Commessariat for Refugees (UNHCR) from entering Mostar, 
city in southwest Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  UNHCR spokeswoman Sylvana Foa said in Geneva that the 
convoys 
were unable to enter both the eastern (Muslim) and western 
(Croat) parts of Mostar. 
  A mental hospital, with some 100 patients, is in the Croat 
part of the city and under constant sniper fire, Foa said. 
  Thirty-seven people, including five children, were killed in 
Mostar in the February 1-5 period, while scores of civilians 
were wounded, she said. 
  Foa confirmed that the humanitarian convoys, which left 
Belgrade on Monday and crossed Bosnian Serb territory without 
mishap, had arrived in the Muslim enclaves of Tuzla and 
Srebrenica (northeast and eastern Bosnia). 
  Relief aid convoys for the Bosnian Muslims are regularly 
provided free and unhindered passage through Bosnian Serb 
territory, official UNHCR and U.N. Protection Force reports said. 
  Foa added that the severe snowstorms in central Bosnia on 
Tuesday stopped seven humanitarian convoys which left Metkovici 
(on the Adriatic coast) for Muslim-held Zenica. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

