<H3> <TI>   Russia's Churkin Views Sarajevo Massacre </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402201394 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1402201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Excerpt" from interview with Vitaliy Churkin, deputy </F>
foreign minister of Russia and special envoy of the Russian 
president, with "Russian television" "during his visit to 
Belgrade" on 13 February -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Studio announcer] During his visit to Belgrade, 
Vitaliy Churkin, deputy foreign minister of Russia and special 
envoy of the Russian president, gave an interview to Russian 
television. In the newscast we will show the part that refers to 
the massacre in Sarajevo [5 February] and Russia's 
interpretation of NATO's decision. The interview will be shown 
in full in the Svet Danas program today. 
  [Begin Churkin recording, in Russian with superimposed 
Serbo-Croatian translation] I think that it is almost certain 
that this was not done by the Serbs, because, as a rule, if this 
were the Serbs, the experts who were investigating this case 
would have quickly come up with such conclusions. 
  It is necessary to demilitarize the area around Sarajevo. We 
envisage this as a two-way operation that does not apply to the 
Serbs alone, but also to the Muslims. Therefore, I think the 
international community will understand that not only this 
bloody wound of Sarajevo would begin to heal, but, in our view, 
better conditions would be created for a better political 
solution. 
  Therefore, the events that should happen in Sarajevo, its 
demilitarization, are in the interest of both the Serbs 
themselves and those who favor a political solution. 

</TEXT>

