<DATE1>  15 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Palwak Meets With Slovenian Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1402191394 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1719 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1402191394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 14 Feb--Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
received this afternoon Lojze Peterle, deputy premier and 
foreign minister of the Republic of Slovenia. 
  After the meeting, the Slovenian diplomat told journalists 
that Prime Minister Pawlak had expressed interest in closer 
cooperation with Slovenia, in particular in the economic field. 
According to Peterle, both sides spoke in favor of strengthening 
economic cooperation in the whole of Central Europe, at the same 
time admitting that there was still a lot to be done "with 
regard to economic reforms." 
  The Slovenian minister confirmed the willingness to conclude 
an agreement on free trade with Poland. Slovenia already 
concluded similar agreements with the Czech Republic and 
Slovakia and will soon sign one with Hungary. "It seems that the 
expansion of the free trade zone is necessary, as it makes our 
access to the European Union easier," he said. 
  Peterle announced that Polish-Slovenian political 
cooperation 
would concentrate on the forum of the Central-European 
Initiative. He said that there were good foundations for this 
cooperation, as both states had similar views on Europe and the 
issue of security. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31125 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu031_p_94007" </HT>


