<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Refuse To Withdraw; Tension Increasing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Mladic: `Nothing Can Force Us To Leave' </H4>
<F P=102> LD1502163394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1547 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1502163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 15 Feb (TANJUG) -- There will be no 
withdrawal of Serb artillery, Colonel General Ratko Mladic, 
chief of the general staff of the army of the Srpska republic, 
said today following his meeting with UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Forces] commanders in Lukavica. 
  "We are not going to leave our people without protection. 
They have always lived in this area. We have no right to do 
such a thing and nothing can force us to leave our people at the 
mercy of fanatical Muslim units." 
  Mladic talked today to Generals Jean Cot and Michael Rose, 
UNPROFOR commanders for the former Yugoslavia and 
ex-Bosnia-Herzegovina. Vitaliy Churkin, Russia's deputy 
minister for foreign affairs, attended part of this meeting. 

</TEXT>

