<H3> <TI>   Todorov, FRY Minister View Academic Contacts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0902173094 Sofia BTA in English 1625 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0902173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, February 9 (BTA) -- "The first visit to 
Bulgaria by the minister of education and culture of the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia, Prof. Dr. Slavko Gordic, aims to study 
the possibilities of cooperation between Bulgaria and Yugoslavia 
in science and education," Marko Todorov, Bulgaria's minister of 
science and education, said after his first meeting with Prof. 
Gordic today. He laid particular stress on the issue of the 
Bulgarian minority in Yugoslavia and the necessity to resolve 
the problem of teachers and textbooks of the Bulgarian language 
and literature, history and geography for the Bulgarians living 
in the Western Outlands (given to Serbia under the Treaty of 
Neuilly of 1919). The exchange of lecturers and students 
between the universities of the two countries was also 
discussed. The guests showed interest in establishing contacts 
with the universities in Sofia and Veliko Turnovo and the 
Bulgarian Academy of Sciences. 
  Prof. Gordic told reporters that his talks with the 
Bulgarian 
minister of science and education passed in an atmosphere of 
understanding setting a basis for the promotion of relations to 
the interest of both countries. 

</TEXT>

