<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus: Air Strikes Against Serbs `Unfair' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002161094 Prague CTK in English 1459 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 10 (CTK) -- Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus 
said today the government and the Civic Democratic Party (ODS), 
of which Klaus is chairman, believe the civil war in Bosnia 
should not be resolved by external intervention but by internal 
settlement. 
  In his personal view the air strikes which the NATO Council 
threatened Bosnian Serbs with unless they withdraw heavy 
artillery from surrounding Sarajevo are "unfair". "Personally I 
see it as a little unfair to say: Ground troops no but from the 
air yes. That seems too easy to me and I don't know if it is 
fair," Klaus said. 
  Given the non-existence of a front and the unclear positions 
of the armies, the government considers external intervention 
could lead to "far greater massacres and catastrophes," Klaus 
said. 
  On Wednesday [9 February] the NATO Council gave the Bosnian 
Serbs 10 days from February 10 to withdraw all heavy artillery 
including tanks and mortars to a distance of 20 km from the 
center of the besieged Bosnian city of Sarajevo and deliver them 
into the control of UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] troops, NATO 
will conduct air strikes against their positions. 

</TEXT>

