<H3> <TI>   Government Opposes Special Law on Minorities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002174294 Prague CTK in English 2009 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 9 (CTK) -- The Czech Government is 
opposed to the creation of a special law on ethnic minorities or 
of an institution to deal with related questions, Prime Minister 
Vaclav Klaus said today. 
  The government reached the conclusion after studying 
material 
on ethnic minorities submitted to it by Minister Igor Nemec, 
chairman of the Government Ethnic Minorities Council, Klaus 
said. He stressed that the government unequivocally supported 
"a policy of ethnic minorities' non-discrimination." 
  According to the 1991 census, the Czech Republic had 10.3 
million citizens. The strongest ethnic minorities were Slovaks 
(314,877), Poles (59,383), and Germans (48,566). 

</TEXT>

