<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliamentary Committee Debates Media Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002192594 Budapest MTI in English 1812 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 10 Feb (MTI) -- No media law seems 
imminent, and temporary regulation of the media for the election 
campaign is also uncertain, parliament's Cultural Committee 
concludes. 
  The opposition Hungarian Socialist Party (HSP) collected 
50,000 authenticated signatures for parliament to include a 
media bill in its agenda. Meanwhile, the government has also 
submitted its media bill draft, to be discussed by Parliament in 
the near future. 
  HSP's Ferenc Kosa wants Hungary to have a media law before 
the election campaign. If not, supervisory committees could be 
set up to ensure ethical campaigning on radio and television, he 
presumed. 
  Miklos Haraszti of the main opposition party, the Alliance 
of 
Free Democrats (AFD), noted that the government had a new 
version of the media law differing from the original consensus 
at several points. As the bill can only pass if supported by 
two-thirds of deputies, he felt preliminary consultations were 
inevitable. 
  Attila Zsigmond of the ruling Hungarian Democratic Forum 
said 
the HDF was ready for discussions, but he was not authorised to 
announce this officially. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

