<H3> <TI>   Solidarity `Willing To Talk' With Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1002185194 Warsaw PAP in English 1702 GMT 10 feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1002185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 10 -- Solidarity leader Marian 
Krzaklewski on Thursday declared that his trade union was 
"willing to talk" with the government. 
  Krzaklewski sent a letter to Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
in which he said that in connection with "tense relations" 
between the government and Solidarity he declared the 
willingness of his trade union to talk and to exchange clear 
positions of both sides, as well as to find solutions to present 
and potential conflicts. 
  Krzaklewski pointed out that the present serious situation 
requires urgent negotiations. 

</TEXT>

