<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Leader on `Rather Durable' Coalition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0902175094 Warsaw PAP in English 1735 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0902175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 9 -- According to head of the Party of 
Christian Democrats (PCHD) Pawel Laczkowski, the coalition of 
the Democratic Left Alliance (SLD) and the Polish Peasant Party 
(PSL) is rather durable. Laczkowski said on Wednesday he did 
not expect the coalition to break up soon, although he was not 
sure whether it could survive four years. 
  He explained that by relative durability he meant the 
ability 
to adopt budget and to cope with local government elections. He 
did not expect any crack to take place this year as too many 
parties were waiting as alternative candidates, for instance, 
the Confederation for an Independent Poland (KPN). 
  The PCHD leader believes that internal shifting took place 
in 
the coalition and that Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak emerged 
strengthened from the dispute. He would get even stronger if 
Henryk Chmielak (first deputy finance minister) were appointed 
as finance minister. 
  Laczkowski added that another major crack, for instance over 
the agrarian policy, could take place, but he did not see major 
threats to the coalition's relative durability. 

</TEXT>

