<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Opposes Plan for Referendum on Mandate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002085794 Prague CTK in English 2122 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Casta-Papiernicka, West Slovakia Feb 9 (CTK) -- The 
parliamentary groups of the government coalition parties and the 
cabinet today started a two-day meeting aimed at finding a way 
out of the current parliamentary crisis in Slovakia. 
  The meeting was joined by Premier Vladimir Meciar after his 
return from Brussels, where he signed the Partnership for Peace 
plan at NATO's headquarters. 
  The Slovak parliament was stalemated last week when the 
deputies from the government Movement For a Democratic Slovakia 
(HZDS) and the Slovak National Party (SNS) walked out of the 
parliament at the moment when the coalition's and the 
opposition's balance of forces was 75-75. 
  Ivan Laluha, former chairman of the HZDS Group, told 
journalists that "this situation cannot prevail. It is not 
possible that a decision on whether or not the government 
remains be made at every parliamentary meeting, because this 
hampers the process of transformation. Early elections are one 
of possible solutions." 
  Laluha as well as Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik came out 
against Meciar's proposal to solve the situation through a 
referendum. 
  In it citizens would decide on whether or not the deputies 
who left the parties and movements for which they had been 
elected to the parliament should leave the parliament. In this 
way, the government camp would gain back the parliamentary 
majority. 

</TEXT>

