<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   HZDS Officials Resign as Party Seeks Unity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002180594 Prague CTK in English 1551 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Casta Papiernicka, west Slovakia, Feb 10 (CTK) -- 
Vladimir Bajan and Marian Kelemen, the deputy chairmen of the 
ruling Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), resigned from 
their positions at the meeting of the HZDS Club of Deputies, a 
spokeswomen for the party told journalists today. 
  The meeting, which started on Wednesday (9 February), was 
originally expected to deal with the creation of a parliamentary 
majority, but it is, in fact, busy with maintaining the unity of 
the HZDS. 
  The meeting was attended by Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik, 
Transport Minister Roman Hofbauer, Agriculture Minister Jozef 
Baco and Deputy Prime Minister Roman Kovac today. In addition, 
representatives of the Slovak National Party (SNS), the minor 
coalition party, were present but when the internal HZDS affairs 
were discussed, they left the room. 
  According to the independent daily NARODNA OBRODA, the 
"alternative faction" in the HZDS led by Moravcik and Kovac came 
into being on Wednesday. No one has, however, confirmed the 
information. 
  The paper claimed that the 16-deputies-strong faction 
advocated the idea of creating a broad government coalition 
without participation of party leaders. They consider the 
solution to be temporary as they assume early elections called 
for early 1995. 

</TEXT>

