<H3> <TI>   Poll: One-Third Back Ban on Hungarian Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0902173994 Prague CTK in English 1300 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0902173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 9 (CTK) -- More than one-third of 
ethnic Slovaks think that the activities of ethnic Hungarian 
political parties in Slovakia should be banned, while 27 percent 
of Hungarians think that Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar's 
Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) should be banned, the 
independent daily SME writes today. Twenty-one percent of 
Hungarians favor a ban on the coalition Slovak National Party 
(SNS), the paper writes. 
  The public opinion research was carried out by Glasgow 
University in cooperation with the Gallup polling firm between 
December 2 and 12, 1993. According to the poll of 667 Slovak 
citizens, HZDS supporters are more likely to favor a ban on 
ethnic Hungarian parties. Fifty-two percent of HZDS voters 
polled expressed this view. 
  Forty-three percent of SNS supporters, 36 percent of 
Democratic Left Party (SDL) supporters, and 18 percent of 
Christian Democratic Movement (KDH) supporters shared this view. 

</TEXT>

