<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daskalov Returns, Comments on Geneva Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1202185694 Sofia BTA in English 1731 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1202185694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, February 12 (BTA) -- I took part in informal 
discussions which may help the peaceful solution of the conflict 
in the former Yugoslavia, Foreign Minister Stanislav Daskalov 
said today upon his arrival from Geneva, where he attended a 
meeting of the foreign ministers of the countries neighbouring 
on Yugoslavia, organized by Lord Owen and Thorvald Stoltenberg. 
According to Mr. Daskalov, the meeting was useful and the 
participants expressed a wish to hold, if necessary, similar 
meetings in future as well. 
  The main issues discussed at the meeting were how the 
neighbouring countries could help the solution of the crisis in 
the former Yugoslavia and the impact of the Yugo-embargo on 
them. A report was circulated unofficially estimating the 
Yugo-embargo losses sustained by the neighbouring countries, 
Foreign Minister Daskalov said. Each of the participating 
countries is to make its comments on this report. 
  Bulgaria has invariably been for a peaceful solution and 
non-intervention in the conflict in the former Yugoslavia. But 
should the need arise to resort to restricted air strikes as an 
extreme measure, these should meet a number of conditions, the 
Bulgarian foreign minister said regarding the NATO ultimatum. 
According to him, these conditions are that the air strikes 
result in no casualties among the peaceful population, that they 
do not lead to the spread of the conflict and that they do not 
threaten neighbouring states. 
  At the meeting no one gave guarantees that neighbouring 
countries would not be affected, Foreign Minister Daskalov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

