<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Chief, Daskalov on Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1302160794 Sofia BTA in English 1940 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1302160794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, February 12 (BTA) -- "Air strikes in Bosnia 
would result in a fresh escalation of the conflict but within 
the boundaries of Bosnia-Herzegovina," Bulgarian intelligence 
chief General Brigo Asparukhov said in an interview for the 
Panorama weekly political round-up show of Bulgarian National 
Television. He described as strange the allegations of 24 CHASA 
-- the daily of the largest circulation in Bulgaria, about his 
prediction of a Balkan war and Bulgaria's involvement in it. 
Last Thursday [10 February] 24 CHASA reported of a statement 
made by General Asparukhov at a closed door session of the 
Parliamentary National Security Committee that "air strikes in 
Bosnia pose the greatest threat to Bulgaria's national security 
in 50 years." "This is the first time in 50 years that war is 
being waged near Bulgaria's borders and this fact should not be 
neglected and should keep us on our guard," the Bulgarian 
intelligence chief said tonight. He called the allegations of 
24 CHASA that his views on Bulgaria's attitude to the 
Yugo-crisis differ from those of Deputy Defence Minister Boyko 
Noev mere speculation. 
  "Bulgaria has always been for a peaceful solution of the 
conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina," Bulgarian Foreign Minister 
Stanislav Daskalov said in Panorama in response to a question on 
possible air strikes against the Bosnian Serbs. He recalled 
that the first section of NATO's resolution of February 9 sets 
the peaceful solution of the crisis as the principal goal of the 
organization. If NATO's decision for air strikes against the 
Bosnian Serbs is brought into operation, there should be 
guarantees that there will be no casualties among the civilian 
population and that these air strikes will not lead to a spread 
of the conflict, Foreign Minister Daskalov said. 
  According to a regular poll among 100 prominent Bulgarian 
journalists, less than 8 percent believe that there will be air 
strikes in Bosnia, 84 percent do not believe this, and 8 percent 
are not sure. 

</TEXT>

