<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Views Intervention in B-H </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1102212294 Prague CTK in English 1809 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1102212294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 11 (CTK) -- The Czech Foreign Ministry 
has said it considers the NATO Council's decision about a 
possible armed intervention in Bosnia-Herzegovina to protect the 
civilian population a serious step which can markedly contribute 
to progress in the Geneva peace talks. 
  In its statement given to CTK today, the ministry reiterated 
its opinion that any external military intervention alone could 
not produce settlement of the situation unless all the three 
feuding parties display will and ability to reach agreement. 
  The ministry said it believed that the warring parties would 
withdraw heavy weaponry from Sarajevo's surroundings within the 
10-day deadline given them by the NATO Council, and that they 
would show real political will not only to introduce an 
effective cease- fire, but to find an acceptable way out of the 
crisis as well. 
  The ministry said it believed that the previous resolutions 
adopted by the UN Security Council provided a sufficient legal 
basis for aerial attacks under conditions set by the United 
Nations earlier. 

</TEXT>

