<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Denies Criticizing NATO Strike Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402211294 Prague CTK in English 2012 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402211294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, February 14 (CTK) -- Czech Premier Vaclav 
Klaus told journalists today he was "fully convinced" that no 
NATO air strikes would be made at Serb positions near Sarajevo. 
  Speaking after a cabinet session, he also said the Czech 
side 
believed that the core to the solution was a "domestic 
agreement," and outside intervention could only supplement, and 
not replace, a domestic solution to the situation. 
  Klaus said no representative of the Czech Republic had 
criticized the NATO Council's decision to bombard the positions 
of Bosnian Serbs if the Council's ultimatum was not upheld. 
"Nobody, including me, has made any statements concerning how we 
would react in the event of attacks," he said. 
  Last Thursday [10 February] Klaus said the Czech Government 
and the Civic Democratic Party (ODS, of which he is chairman) 
were afraid there would be outside military intervention in 
Bosnia and were of the opinion that civil war should not be 
ended by foreign intervention but by settlement at home. He 
said that he personally considered the possible air strikes 
approved by the NATO Council on Wednesday as "unfair from a 
human point of view." 
  Klaus stressed today that it was not the task of the Czech 
Republic to find a way of solving the crisis in Bosnia. As far 
as the difference between the standpoints of President Vaclav 
Havel and Deputy Premier Jan Kalvoda, both of whom support 
NATO's position, and his standpoint was concerned, it was 
unnecessary to consider the difference a dispute. 

</TEXT>

