<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy Welcomes NATO `Readiness' in B-H </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502054394 Prague CTK in English 2124 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1502054394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New York, Feb 14 (CTK) -- The Czech Republic 
welcomes NATO's clear and unambiguous readiness to intervene in 
Bosnia on behalf of the international community, Czech 
Ambassador to the U.N. Security Council Karel Kovanda said at 
the meeting of the Council today. 
  "The threat of unleashing air strikes cannot be seen in 
isolation but as part of wider measures, he said, adding that 
"on its own, it will not solve anything because the solution 
will have to involve all three parties to the conflict," he 
said. [quotation marks as received] 
  "The threatening stance has been agreed on to prevent 
Sarajevo from suffocation and provide it with a chance to come 
under U.N. supervision if the parties involved so wish," he 
said, adding that the U.N.'s threatening stance will help the 
parties to the conflict negotiate a solution. 
  "Allow me to say that we recognized it as a matter beyond 
doubt that since last summer, secretary general has had the 
powers to authorize air raids on heavy artillery positions 
responsible for attacks on civilians," Kovanda said, referring 
to the demands for a new document on the issue. 
  Contrary to the Western states, who are opposed to any such 
move, Russia repeatedly proposed that the Council adopt a new 
resolution on Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

