<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   KDNP Leader Opens Election Campaign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402164994 Budapest MTI in English 1722 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 13 February (MTI) -- "What the Hungarian 
nation wants to have after the May 8 elections is better, more, 
fairer, and more efficient than it has today. It is uncertain, 
though, that it wants something fundamentally different," Laszlo 
Surjan, chairman of the Christian Democratic People's Party 
(KDNP) and welfare minister, told a rally marking the beginning 
of his party's electoral campaign today. 
  The chairman of the smallest party of the governing 
coalition 
said the Christian Democrats rejected Prime Minister Peter 
Boross's statement that the Hungarian Democratic Forum (MDF) is 
the only force able to govern the country. "We consider 
ourselves fit for the task," Surjan said. He added, however, 
that the Christian Democrats stand the closest to the MDF. 
  Outlining the priorities of the KDNP's electoral manifesto, 
Surjan said that the Christian Democrats pressed for a 
calculable legislature, and wished to guarantee a safe and 
calculable future for the people. 
  Making a critical approach to the past four years, the KDNP 
chairman said the state had got rid of its oversized tasks too 
quickly and left society unprepared to face a multitude of 
problems. The Christian Democrats wish that the state should 
assume responsibility for, rather than intervene in, the 
economy. "We want to have a strong rule of law and stable 
public security," Surjan said. 

</TEXT>

