<H3> <TI>   Olechowski Cites Importance of Slovene Accords </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502123794 Warsaw PAP in English 1556 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1502123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 14 -- Foreign ministers of Poland and 
Slovenia, Andrzej Olechowski and Lojze Peterle, respectively, 
signed on Monday [14 February] an agreement on intergovernmental 
cooperation in education, culture and science and a protocol on 
cooperation between the two ministries. 
  Olechowski said that the signed agreements were like "stones 
of which a new Europe was being built." He also stressed that 
they would contribute to building relations between the nations 
that liked each other. 
  Earlier in the day, the two ministers held a meeting and 
chaired the plenary talks by the delegations of the foreign 
ministries of Poland and Slovenia. The talks were attended by 
Polish deputy minister for foreign economic relations Andrzej 
Bryt. 
  The talks focused on preparing bilateral economic agreements 
which were planned to cover protection of investments, avoidance 
of double taxation, transport, transfer of social benefits and 
re- admission. 
  Peterle said the agreements should be signed still this 
year. 
He stressed that the talks and decisions made on Monday were "a 
big step" designed to consolidate Polish-Slovenian and 
international cooperation in Central Europe on the 
Baltic-Adriatic line. 
  The two sides also discussed the situation in the Balkans. 
In the opinion Peterle, the recent developments in Bosnia show 
there is a possibility of reaching peace. He expressed hope 
that the European Community would help limit or even solve the 
conflict. 
  Peterle, who is holding both the post of foreign minister 
and 
deputy prime minister, said Slovenia was planning to establish 
its embassy in Warsaw. Poland announced at the beginning of 
January, 1994, that it decided to open its embassy in Ljubljana. 

</TEXT>

