<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac Calls For Government of Broader Coalition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1202130994 Prague CTK in English 2046 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1202130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 11 (CTK) -- In a statement given to 
CTK today, Slovak Deputy Prime Minister Roman Kovac said that as 
attempts made so far prove that an agreement between the leaders 
of the parliamentary parties and movements was unfeasible, he 
agreed with a pragmatic proposal by the newly emerged 
Alternative of Political Realism. 
  The alternative, established on Thursday [10 February] 
within 
the government coalition major partner, Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), proposes to form a government of a 
broader coalition without top politicians and with the 
participation of independent experts which would operate until 
early elections. 
  Roman Kovac has joined the alternative, along with ten HZDS 
deputies and Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik, also an HZDS 
member. 
  Kovac said he expected the broad coalition government to 
draw 
inspiration from the political programs of the individual 
parties and to try to stabilize the economy and other vitally 
important spheres of society. He called cruel and unjust the 
statement made by Prime Minister and HZDS leader Vladimir Meciar 
that the new coalition's common denominator would be only 
"plundering." 
  Although he is attracted by the ideas embedded in the HZDS 
statutes, he has the right to his own opinion and to defend it, 
Kovac said. He underlined he saw that realization of the appeal 
of the alternative was an acceptable way of deblocking the 
operation of the parliament. He does not find it either 
undemocratic or immoral, he added. 
  "On the contrary, everybody bound to shoulder social and 
political responsibility, should fulfill it according to his 
(her) best conscience," Kovac says in the statement. 

</TEXT>

