<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   SNS Supports HZDS Call for Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402185194 Prague CTK in English 1300 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1402185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 14 (CTK) -- "If the opposition 
believes that the opinions of voters differ from those of 
parliamentary deputies, early elections could take place," Jozef 
Prokes, Slovak deputy premier and honorary chairman of the 
government coalition's junior partner, the Slovak National Party 
(SNS), told journalists today. 
  Prokes said that the SNS fully agreed with the view of its 
coalition partner, the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia 
(HZDS), that the elections should be called as early as possible. 
  He said that the vote of no confidence in Deputy Premier 
Roman Kovac and Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik by the HZDS 
Board on Saturday [12 February] was a natural result of the 
developments within the HZDS. 
  Roman Kovac and Moravcik [are] the initiators of a new 
faction within the HZDS aimed at creating a broad coalition 
government. 
  Prokes said that the SNS and the HZDS had not yet discussed 
possible successors to Kovac and Moravcik if they are dismissed. 
It is premature to evaluate the question of whether the post of 
foreign minister will be offered to himself, Prokes stated. 
  Reacting to the proposals made by the newly established HZDS 
faction, the Alternative of Political Realism, Prokes said that 
the country had already experienced a National Front in the 
communist period. If such steps are taken now, it would be the 
end of pluralism, he added. 
  Prokes assured that the eight-member SNS group of deputies 
would support the amendment to the large privatization law, 
which is to be the first point on the agenda of the next meeting 
within the current parliamentary session, scheduled for 
Wednesday [16 February]. 

</TEXT>

