<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia's Tudjman Talks With Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1502134294 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1200 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1502134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, on the second day of his visit to Romania, 
Croatian President Franjo Tudjman and the Croatian delegation 
visited the Romanian parliament. They met the president of the 
House of Deputies, Adrian Nastase, and President of the Senate 
Oliviou Gherman. President Tudjman visited the House of 
Representatives, which was in session. He was welcomed with 
rapturous applause. Nastase said that all matters of political 
importance were discussed in the parliament comprising 14 
parties and 460 representatives. He said that the main issues 
being discussed by the representatives were the democratic 
development of Romania and economic reforms. [words indistinct] 
the right way, he stressed, and added that all political 
disputes are resolved by political means in parliament and that 
there is a general consensus among the parties on foreign policy. 
  In his temporary residence in Bucharest, President Tudjman 
received Romanian Prime Minister Nicolae Vacaroiu. Discussing 
the crisis in the former Yugoslavia, they agreed that the 
international community had reacted too late and that there is 
disunity regarding solutions between the United Nations, 
European union, and the United States. The Croatian president 
and the Romanian prime minister also discussed economic 
relations between the two countries. Tonight the Croatian 
president will meet representatives of the Croatian community in 
Romania at the Croatian embassy in Bucharest. 

</TEXT>

