<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Warns Citizens on Bombing, Downed Planes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1502163294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1301 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1502163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bileca, 15 Feb (TANJUG) -- The Command of the 
Herzegovina Corps today issued a cautionary note to the 
population of this area. It says that protective measures 
should be immediately taken to provide maximum protection for 
people and property from possible attacks by the NATO air force. 
  It stresses that it is necessary to tidy up cellars and 
communal shelters and secure the most basic quantities of food 
and equipment for administering first aid to the wounded. In 
the event of attack one should behave sensibly and follow 
instructions by civil defense officials. 
  The Command of the Herzegovina Corps believes that the 
territory of Serbian Herzegovina can be threatened by deliberate 
bombardment as well as by technical faults along the flight path 
of NATO aircraft. It also points out the possibility of 
aircraft carrying lethal loads being shot down or crashing into 
each other and their dropping lethal loads at random on 
inhabited settlements. 
  "Serb units are taking every measure to protect free 
territory and the population from possible attacks by the NATO 
air force and they will warn the population in time about any 
possible threat from the air," the Command of the Herzegovina 
Corps says in its warning announcement. 

</TEXT>

