<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties Condemn Ultimatum To Bosnian Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1402235094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2341 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1402235094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, February 14 (TANJUG) -- Several parties 
from the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia on Monday strongly 
condemned the NATO threats to bomb Serb positions in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, pointing out that this would jeopardize the 
search for a peaceful solution to the crisis in this former 
Yugoslav republic. 
  President of the opposition parliamentary Democratic Party 
Zoran Djindjic said that the NATO ultimatum "is contrary to U.N. 
Security Council resolutions and dangerously threatens the peace 
process" in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Speaking at a meeting in Knjazevac, a town in southeastern 
Serbia, Djindjic assessed that it was evident that the ultimatum 
did not have any humanitarian or security foundations, but was 
primarily a tool to "pressure the Serb negotiators in Geneva." 
  "Serbia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia must join the 
efforts to oppose this dangerous and irresponsible policy of the 
NATO pact," he said. 
  The League of Communists-Movement for Yugoslavia most 
sharply 
condemns the by-passing of the U.N. in seeking a solution for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, said a statement released by the party, 
assessing that the ultimatum was a "threat to all small peoples 
and states if they do not bow to the will of the mighty." 
  "As in World War II, the Communists will place themselves at 
the head of the battle against any foreign aggressor and in the 
interest of the people they will resolutely oppose Western 
military powers and all supporters of the civil war in former 
Yugoslavia," said the statement. 
  The Democratic Party of Yugoslavia sent an appeal to all 
warring sides in Bosnia-Herzegovina to see reason and opt for 
compromise and agreement by easing tensions at all points. 
  The Party of Serb Unity warned that peace could not be 
achieved with threats and ultimatums. 
  "If only one bomb falls on Serb positions and homes in 
Bosnia, the Party of Serb Unity will put into operation its 
military agreement with the Liberal-Democratic Party of Russia 
and call Russian volunteers to stand in the defence of the 
Christian Orthodox religion, side by side with their Serb 
brethren," said a party statement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

