<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRY Official Views Talks With Croatia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1202233994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2201 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1202233994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Belgrade, 12 Feb -- Zeljko Simic, deputy prime 
minister of the Federal Government [of Yugoslavia], said at 
[Belgrade's] Surcin airport this evening that serious and 
detailed talks were held today in Zagreb and that they 
represented the realization of previous negotiations. 
  A commission for missing persons and humanitarian issues was 
formally and legally constituted and it would work under the 
auspices of the International Committee of the Red Cross [ICRC] 
and the UNHCR [UN High Commissioner for Refugees]. 
  The commission has eight members--three each from Yugoslavia 
and from Croatia and one each from the ICRC and the UNHCR. 
  Simic also said that all details in connection with the 
opening of offices in Belgrade and Zagreb were agreed and that 
they would be opened, most likely at the end of this or at the 
beginning of next month. [passage omitted] 
  Simic said that his talks with Croatian President Tudjman 
were successful, pointing out that the Croatian president showed 
that he was very interested in the normalization of relations 
with Yugoslavia. 
  Simic also said that after these talks he was even more 
convinced that meetings at the highest level were, he said, 
"more than realistic." 
  Asked whether the status of the Republic of Serb Krajina 
[RSK] was discussed, Simic said that the Yugoslav standpoints 
were clear but not so inflexible that they could prevent a 
normalization of relations. 
  The issue of Krajina is very sensitive but the RSK is a 
political reality and must be respected, Simic stressed, and 
went on to say that the current situation did not suit Zagreb 
but an aggressive resolution of the situation would suit Zagreb 
even less. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

