<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visits With Milosevic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1502200694 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1502200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias will tonight 
return from Belgrade where he held talks with the leadership of 
the new Yugoslavia in his capacity as the European Union [EU] 
Council of Ministers president and as the Greek foreign 
minister. Papoulias will meet Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic at 2100 today. 
  Papoulias said his talks in Belgrade were held in a warm 
atmosphere. Within the framework of the new Greek initiative to 
avert NATO intervention in Bosnia, Papoulias held talks with 
Serb President Slobodan Milosevic and said that both he and 
Milosevic ascertained that times are difficult but there is hope 
that worse might be avoided. He said: This will not only 
benefit Europe, but the Balkans too. 
  The foreign minister said the Greek Presidency is 
considering 
convening the EU Council of Ministers before the NATO ultimatum 
expires. Papoulias said the procedure to withdraw the heavy 
weaponry from Sarajevo is proceeding well and this is hopeful. 
But he noted that this is not solely the Serb side's 
responsibility and that the Muslims should do the same to save 
peace and the EU peace plan, on which the Greek side insists. 
  Asked if Greece will exercise its veto right at NATO against 
the air raids, Papoulias said Greece is considering using every 
available means to avert extensive clashes. The foreign 
minister said he and Milosevic discussed the possibility of the 
war spreading to the south, stressing that this would be a 
dramatic development -- the beginning of an armed clash that 
would have broader European dimensions. Papoulias said no one 
can rule out the participation of third forces. 
  Replying to another question, Papoulias said the Greeks in 
Serbia are safe. He said: They consider it their second home 
and there is no need to abandon it. Papoulias said citizens 
from other Western countries are evacuated following their 
countries' evaluations and decisions. 

</TEXT>

