<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baudys Calls Ultimatum `Correct' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502164994 Prague LIDOVE NOVINY in Czech 12 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1502164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague LIDOVE NOVINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "jop": "Baudys Approves of NATO's Decision"] </F>
  [Text] Dobruska--"I am convinced that NATO considered its 
decision to issue an ultimatum to one of the parties in the 
Sarajevo conflict for a long time. This decision is correct. 
Furthermore, I believe that the Alliance secretly assumed that 
the Serbs would take a positive stand on the withdrawal of their 
heavy military equipment," Czech Defense Minister Antonin Baudys 
said yesterday while visiting Dobruska. Replying to a question 
from the LIDOVE NOVINY reporter as to whether an emergency plan 
for our soldiers serving with UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] in 
former Yugoslavia had been drawn up, Antonin Baudys said: "Our 
troops are outside Bosnia-Herzegovina, in the area of the 
so-called Serbian Krajina. Should a conflict come about, the 
Czech side would proceed in the same way as the troops of other 
countries under UN command." 

</TEXT>

