<H3> <TI>   President Havel Comments on Visit to Kuwait </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1502144094 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 0600 
GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1502144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Announcer] President of the Republic Vaclav 
Havel returned during the night from his eight-day official 
visit to India and Thailand. Czech radio correspondent David 
Stahlavsky, who accompanied the president during his trip, is in 
the studio now with more details. 
  [Stahlavsky] President Havel considers the visit to be a 
success. He reiterated this tonight shortly before landing at 
Old Ruzyne airport. He praised, in particular, the 
participation of Ivan Kocarnik, deputy prime minister and 
finance minister; Josef Zieleniec, minister of foreign affairs; 
and Radomir Sabela, deputy of the minister of industry and 
trade. They all agree with the president's assessment of the 
visit. [passage omitted] 
  Vaclav Havel made a brief unofficial stopover in Kuwait. He 
had private talks with the amir in power, Shaykh Jabir al-Ahmad 
al-Jabir al-Sabah. This is what the Czech president said about 
these talks: 
  [Begin recording] [Havel] The amir and I discussed political 
cooperation between our countries. We agreed that our views 
were very close and that no political shadows exist between us. 
We also discussed economic cooperation. I said that this 
cooperation is not as good as it could be, that unutilized 
potential exists in this respect. I explained the reasons we 
did not use this potential as best we could during the period 
that our entire economy was undergoing the process of 
transformation. The amir emphasized that Kuwait is very 
interested in economic cooperation with the Czech Republic and 
that our firms are well known in that country. An agreement 
between Kuwait and the Czech Republic on the protection of 
investments is due to be finalized and signed in the spring. 
[passage indistinct] [end recording] 
  [Announcer] It should be added that our trade with Kuwait 
amounted to approximately $5 million last year. Czech exports 
to Kuwait account for the best part of it, while Kuwaiti imports 
to the Czech Republic are very small. 

</TEXT>

