<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deregulation Leads to Accelerated Price Growth </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602085494 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 11 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602085494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "tma": "Prices Rose Almost 2 Percent in </F>
January"] 
  [Text] Prague--Consumer prices rose 1.9 percent in 
January. While food prices remained virtually unchanged, 
compared with December 1993, there were marked increases in 
housing rents, water and sewage rates, the cost of heat, 
municipal transport fares, and other services. 
  Payments for housing rents and related services rose 30 
percent in the course of a single month. This was made possible 
by the government's decision to partially liberalize regulated 
prices in this area. A similar situation pertains to the cost 
of heat and hot water supply, which is almost 16 percent higher 
than in December 1993. Gasoline prices went up 2 percent, 
chiefly as a result of a change in the consumer tax rate. These 
systemic interventions alone led to 0.8-percent price growth. 
  These systemic changes were compounded in January by other 
extraordinary influences. A number of newspapers and magazines 
raised their prices, for example. Overall, these onetime 
changes brought a price growth of over 1 percent. 
  Compared with January 1993, consumer prices are now 10.9 
percent higher. The lowest has been the growth in food prices, 
which went up by less than 5 percent [since January 1993]. 

</TEXT>

