<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Officials Discussing Safety of Aid Workers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602100094 Paris AFP in English 0958 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602100094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Feb 16 (AFP) -- UN officials were meeting 
in the Slovenian border town of Mokrice Wednesday to discuss the 
safety of humanitarian aid workers in Bosnia in view of the 
threat of a NATO air strike against Bosnia's defiant Serbs. 
  "The main issue of the meeting is going to be the safety of 
humanitarian aid workers in Bosnia under present conditions," 
said special UN representative Yasushi Akashi. 
  Akashi was meeting with UN High Commissioner for Refugees 
Sadako Ogata and UN peace mediator Thorvald Stoltenberg. 
Mokrice is about 30 kilometres (18 miles) west of Zagreb. 
  NATO last week issued an ultimatum to Bosnia's warring 
parties, particularly the Serbs, to move their weapons from 
around Sarajevo by midnight Sunday or face air strikes. 

</TEXT>

