<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Disagreements' Disrupt RSK Assembly Session </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1202153494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1359 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1202153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Knin, 12 Feb (TANJUG)--The constituent session of 
the assembly of the republic of Serb Krajina [RSK] has started 
in Knin. The session is chaired by Branko Peric of Knin, the 
oldest deputy. However, the session was interrupted and a 
recess announced due to serious disagreements over the adoption 
of the agenda and the verification of the deputies' mandates. 
  The assembly became divided into two camps: deputies from 
the Serb Democratic Party of Krajina [SDS] and from the Serbian 
Radical Party in one, and deputies from all the other parties 
and citizens' groups in the other. 
  This development dashed hopes that the first session of the 
new Krajina parliament would be held in a jubilant atmosphere 
and that the deputies would transcend party interests--something 
the Chairman Peric had called for at the beginning of the 
session. Drago Kovacevic, head of the SDS group of deputies, 
proposed that the assembly president and deputy presidents be 
elected first and that Milan Martic be sworn in as president 
afterward, while the agenda proposed the opposite. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

