<F P=100> MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Bulgarian Envoy Reviews Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502212994 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1700 
GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1502212994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 15 February in Skopje Macedonian President Kiro 
Gligorov received Angel Dimitrov, the newly appointed Bulgarian 
ambassador to Macedonia, who presented his credentials. The 
meeting was attended by Foreign Minister Stevo Crvenkovski, our 
reporter Kostadin Filipov reports. 
  [Begin Filipov recording] In his speech Ambassador Angel 
Dimitrov stressed that Bulgaria had been the first state to 
recognize the Republic of Macedonia, and the first direct 
neighbor of Macedonia that had established full diplomatic 
relations with that state. 
  This is an expression of the Republic of Bulgaria's 
prudence, 
farsightedness, and determination to develop relations with the 
Republic of Macedonia on the basis of mutual respect and sincere 
friendship -- the only possibility of asserting peace and 
stability on the Balkan peninsula, Ambassador Dimitrov pointed 
out. 
  Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov stressed the unique 
personal contribution of Bulgarian President Zhelyu Zhelev, with 
whom he said he has relations of sincere friendship and 
understanding. He also pointed out Macedonia's great interest 
in maintaining stable and goodneighborly relations with 
Bulgaria. Mr. Gligorov also expressed Macedonia's interest in 
developing and strengthening cooperation in all areas of mutual 
interest and benefit. 
  Now a broad field opens for cultural, economic, scientific, 
and other cooperation, connecting the two countries with the 
necessary railroad, modern highways, and telecommunications, 
Kiro Gligorov stressed. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

