<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unemployment Registered at 16 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1502201794 Warsaw PAP in English 1837 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1502201794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 15--The number of unemployed stood at 
2.9 million in January, up 2.4 percent on December figure, the 
Central Statistical Office (GUS) announced on Tuesday. 
  In January the rate of unemployment was 16 percent, an 
increase of 1.9 percent on December. 
  Also on Tuesday Deputy Labour Minister Jerzy Szreter told a 
press conference that the rise in unemployment probably had a 
seasonal character, and should be halted in March. 
  However, he feared that the anticipated number of unemployed 
of 3.05 million at the end of 1994 might be "threatened" unless 
more money was allocated for active forms of combatting 
unemployment. 
  Unemployment rose in 48 provinces in January with the 
highest 
growth in Chelm (by 6.3 percent) and Cracow (5.3 percent) 
provinces. The highest rate of unemployment was recorded in 
Koszalin (29.3 percent) and Suwalki (28.9 percent) provinces, 
the lowest in Cracow (7.6 percent) and Warsaw (7.9 percent) 
provinces. 

</TEXT>

