<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev Responds to Demirel on B-H Conflict </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602173694 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1700 
GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1602173694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Zhelyu Zhelev has sent a message to 
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel, the president's Press Center 
reports. 
  The message points out that Bulgaria's position on the 
crisis 
in former Yugoslavia is a consistent and principled one. 
Bulgaria opposes the direct participation of Balkan countries 
and countries bordering on former Yugoslavia in eventual 
military measures aimed at establishing peace in the region. 
  The Bulgarian president thinks that even partially lifting 
the arms embargo for the fighting sides would tend to exacerbate 
the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The message assesses the ultimatum of the NATO Council as 
the 
last and radical warning for forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina that 
do not accept the UN Security Council resolution and hinder 
peace negotiations. 
  In conclusion, President Zhelev expresses confidence that 
after signing the Partnership for Peace, relations between 
Bulgaria and NATO will enter a new and more sound stage that 
will also positively affect relations with Turkey. 

</TEXT>

