<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik: No Removal of Heavy Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1702115494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1003 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1702115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jagodina, 17 Feb (TANJUG) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, 
president of the assembly of the Srpska republic, today 
expressed optimism with regard to the international community's 
standpoint that the question of demilitarization of the Sarajevo 
area be resolved by diplomacy rather than by bombardment, as 
envisaged under a NATO ultimatum. 
  I am optimistic -- Krajisnik said in his statement today to 
Jagodina Radio -- as I believe that the international community 
will realize that the Serbs have accepted everything that is 
required of them. 
  "We have agreed to the proposal that Sarajevo be placed 
under 
UN administration; we have accepted an agreement on the future 
organization of Bosnia-Herzegovina; we have signed with the 
Croat side an agreement on the cessation of hostilities until 
political solutions are found; we have agreed that our aircraft 
should not fly over Bosnia-Herzegovina; and finally, we have 
agreed that our weaponry be placed under UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Forces] control." 
  "All this must be enough for the international community to 
realize who is cooperative and which side wants to put an end to 
the war as soon as possible. This is why I am positive that the 
European Union [EU] and the United Nations will find a 
diplomatic solution which will avert NATO's threat to bomb Serb 
positions. Otherwise such an act would be the grossest crime in 
the 20th century in Europe, as aggression would be committed at 
a time when the two warring parties, the Serbs and Muslims, have 
signed a cease-fire, and when there are no combat actions in 
this area." 
  Asked whether heavy weaponry would be removed 20 kilometers 
from Sarajevo or placed under UNPROFOR control, Krajisnik said: 
  "NATO demands that we withdraw our heavy artillery by 20 
kilometers from Sarajevo is in fact demanding that Serb units be 
disarmed. At the same time this means that the Serb side should 
abandon its centuries-old ethnic lands and hand over Sarajevo to 
the Muslim republic. We do not accept this as this amounts to 
capitulation. We are nevertheless willing to allow UNPROFOR 
representatives to control our heavy weaponry, which would 
guarantee that there would be no combat activities from our 
positions," Momcilo Krajisnik told Jagodina Radio. 

</TEXT>

