<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   No `Green Light' for Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602154894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1407 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1602154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Stevan Cordas] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 16 (TANJUG) -- The U.N. Security 
Council [UNSC] has failed to give the green light to NATO to 
launch air strikes against the Bosnian Serbs, diplomatic circles 
in Belgrade said on Wednesday. 
  They interpret this by the fact that a decision was not 
reached even after the two-day Security Council session on the 
Bosnian crisis and the NATO ultimatum. 
  The diplomats believe that, in view of such an outcome of 
the 
Security Council session, the NATO bombardment of the Serb 
positions would represent an aggression, rather than a move 
towards a peaceful solution to the Bosnian crisis. 
  The (un)expected [as received] outcome of the session also 
means that Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali was not given 
permission to order the NATO air strikes. 
  China's Security Council representative openly said that 
Peking [as received] opposes the NATO bombardment. 
  In talks with British Prime Minister John Major, Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin said that a solution to the Bosnian 
crisis cannot be sought without Russia. 
  The diplomats in Belgrade believe that Peking's and Moscow's 
firm stands were clearly decisive for the outcome of the latest 
Security Council session. 
  In the meantime, the world has already started the countdown 
for the NATO ultimatum. 
  In NATO bases in Italy there are as many as 170 war planes. 
  Four more days remain until the deadline expires, but it is 
uncertain whether NATO will attack the Serb positions around 
Sarajevo without a direct Security Council decision. 
  Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias, who was in 
Belgrade 
on Tuesday, said that the NATO ultimatum cannot be interpreted 
as directed only against the Bosnian Serbs. He claims that the 
ultimatum was given to all three warring sides. 
  Papoulias' interpretation is identical to NATO's decision to 
threaten the Bosnian Serbs and Muslims with air strikes unless 
they withdraw their heavy weapons from around Sarajevo to 20 km 
away from the city's centre. However, everyone abroad is 
speaking only about the ultimatum to the Bosnian Serbs, while 
the Muslims and Croats are not mentioned at all. 
  Croatia also faces sanctions if it fails to comply with a 
U.N. demand to pull out its regular troops from Bosnia by 
February 16. 
  However, Croatia is hardly likely to meet this demand and it 
is even more improbable that it will be punished for this 
because some Western countries have already come up with reasons 
for Croatia's failure to withdraw. They are saying that the 
presence of regular Croat troops in Bosnia is good because they 
are "holding back" the Bosnian Croat forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31322 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu033_i_94006" </HT>


