<H3> <TI>   Karadzic, Abdic Sign Cease-Fire Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1702132394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1245 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1702132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 17 Feb (TANJUG) -- Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the Srpska republic, and Fikret Abdic, president of 
the autonomous province of western Bosnia, have reached an 
agreement on the permanent cessation of hostilities and an 
orientation toward political negotiations. This is underlined 
in a statement issued today by the office of the president of 
the Srpska republic. 
  The agreement on a permanent cease-fire will come into 
effect 
at 1200 [1100 GMT] on 18 February. "This is yet another 
important step toward peace in former Bosnia-Herzegovina," the 
statement says. 
  Abdic promises to secure compliance with the cease-fire not 
only on the territory of the autonomous province of western 
Bosnia, but also on the left bank of the Una River, which is 
currently controlled by remnants of the 5th Corps loyal to the 
Muslim government in Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

