<H3> <TI>   `Critical' Situation Cited </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602191794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1602191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Omer Vatric report from Mostar] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] It is very cold in Mostar, and 
it is freezing in people's flats as there is a real fuel crisis. 
There is no electricity for the eighth month running and it is 
uncertain when there will be any. There is no drinking water 
and no food has come into the town lately. No humanitarian aid 
convoy has come for days. There are increasingly shortages of 
medicine and those most needed are unobtainable for days at a 
time. There is a constant crisis with medicines to cure ulcers, 
epilepsy, (?hypertension), and many other diseases. 
  A special problem is the lack of fuel for the hospital 
generator, municipal vehicles, and other vital needs of the 
town. As the Mostar Commune War Presidency reports, it is 
already the fourth time that the Croatian Defense Council has 
turned back fuel that the UNHCR has tried to take to the 
hospital on the left bank [of the Neretva]. In a word, the 
situation in Mostar is critical and it is becoming increasingly 
difficult every day. 

</TEXT>

