<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   NSC Cited on Importance of Central Europe. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602162494 Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY in Czech 15 Feb 94 p 
23 </F>

<F P=103> AU1602162494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague HOSPODARSKE NOVINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [CTK Washington dispatch: "United States: Paying Attention </F>
to Central and Eastern Europe"] 
  [Text] Washington--The formation of a high-level U.S. 
Government group to deal with the affairs of Central and East 
Europe was confirmed by Richard Shifter, a high-ranking 
representative of the U.S. President's National Security 
Council, in Washington on Sunday [13 February]. 
  In a speech at the outset of a conference on the trade and 
economic aspects of developments in Central and East Europe, 
which is organized by the Washington-based organization European 
Institute, Shifter said that this group would be headed by Under 
Secretary of State Peter Tarnoff. 
  Shifter, who is director for Central and East Europe in the 
National Security Council, declared that the formation of this 
group was the result of an overall revision of U.S. foreign 
policy carried out after the accession of Bill Clinton's 
administration. Following this analysis of foreign policy, it 
was decided that special attention must be paid to Central and 
East Europe, Shifter said, and stressed the significance of the 
success of political and democratic reforms in this region for 
the United States. 
  At the same time, he drew attention to the fact that no new 
financial resources from the U.S. budget could be expected in 
support of cooperation with Central and East Europe. The main 
issue is how to make optimal use of existing funds, Shifter 
said, and stressed, in particular, support of the private sector. 
  The decision to form the group for Central and East Europe 
was made about two weeks ago and is to meet for the first time 
within the next few days, Richard Shifter told CTK. 
  All important departments of the U.S. Administration will be 
represented in this group, including the Departments of State, 
Defense, Energy, and Agriculture. 
  The conference on Central and East Europe organized by the 
European Institute is attended also by Czech Minister of 
Industry and Trade Vladimir Dlouhy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31337 </DOCNO>
